reactions_text: ['An example of a synthesis reaction is the formation of iron(II) sulfide from iron and sulfur, represented by the equation 8 Fe + S8 → 8 FeS. This involves multiple iron atoms combining with cyclo-octasulfur to form eight molecules of iron(II) sulfide.', 'Another example of a synthesis reaction is the formation of water from hydrogen and oxygen gases, represented by the equation 2 H2 + O2 → 2 H2O. This involves dihydrogen and dioxygen combining to form water molecules.']

['A synthesis reaction involving the formation of iron(II) sulfide from iron and sulfur, represented as 8 Fe + S8 → 8 FeS. This is an example of two simple substances combining to form a more complex compound.', 'A synthesis reaction involving the reaction of hydrogen and oxygen gases to produce water, represented as 2 H2 + O2 → 2 H2O. This is an example of two simple substances combining to form a more complex compound.']

['The formation of iron(II) sulfide from elemental iron and sulfur. In this reaction, iron atoms and sulfur atoms (from an S8 ring) combine to form a more complex ionic compound, iron(II) sulfide. The balanced equation is 8 Fe + S8 -> 8 FeS. This reaction exemplifies the combination of two simpler substances into a single, more complex product.', 'The synthesis of water from hydrogen gas and oxygen gas. This highly exothermic reaction combines two simple diatomic elements to form a single, more complex molecular compound, water. The overall balanced chemical equation is 2 H2 + O2 -> 2 H2O. It is a canonical example of a synthesis reaction.']

['Iron and sulfur synthesis reaction: Eight atoms of iron metal combine with one molecule of cyclic octasulfur (S8) to produce eight molecules of iron(II) sulfide (FeS). This is a classic example of a direct combination reaction where elemental iron and elemental sulfur combine in an 8:1 stoichiometric ratio to form the ionic compound iron(II) sulfide.', 'Hydrogen and oxygen synthesis reaction: Two molecules of hydrogen gas combine with one molecule of oxygen gas to produce two molecules of water. This is a fundamental synthesis reaction where diatomic hydrogen and oxygen gases combine to form water molecules through the formation of covalent O-H bonds.']

['A synthesis (or combination) reaction involves two or more simple substances combining to form a more complex compound, typically represented as A + B → AB. This type of reaction is characterized by multiple reactants yielding a single product. An example is the formation of iron(II) sulfide from iron and sulfur: 8 Fe + S₈ → 8 FeS, where elemental iron (Fe) reacts with elemental sulfur in its most stable form (S₈ ring structure) to produce iron(II) sulfide (FeS), a compound containing Fe²⁺ and S²⁻ ions. This reaction demonstrates how simple elemental substances combine to form a more complex ionic compound.', 'Another example includes the reaction of hydrogen gas (H₂) and oxygen gas (O₂) to produce water (H₂O), represented as 2 H₂ + O₂ → 2 H₂O. In this synthesis reaction, two diatomic gases combine to form a more complex covalent compound, demonstrating how synthesis reactions are vital for forming complex molecules from simpler substances.']

['Formation of iron(II) sulfide from elemental iron and sulfur. This synthesis reaction involves eight iron atoms (Fe) reacting with one sulfur octamer (S₈) to produce eight formula units of iron(II) sulfide (FeS). The reaction demonstrates the classic A + B → AB pattern characteristic of synthesis reactions, where multiple simple reactants combine to form a more complex compound.', 'Formation of water from hydrogen and oxygen gases. This synthesis reaction involves two diatomic hydrogen molecules (H₂) reacting with one diatomic oxygen molecule (O₂) to produce two water molecules (H₂O). This is a classic example of a synthesis reaction where two simple substances (gases) combine to form a more complex compound, following the pattern A + B → AB.']

['Formation of iron(II) sulfide through synthesis reaction: Eight iron atoms (Fe) react with one molecule of elemental sulfur (S₈, cyclo-octasulfur) to produce eight formula units of iron(II) sulfide (FeS). This demonstrates a classic synthesis reaction where simple elemental substances combine to form a more complex compound, following the general pattern A + B → AB.', 'Formation of water through synthesis reaction: Two molecules of hydrogen gas (H₂) react with one molecule of oxygen gas (O₂) to produce two molecules of water (H₂O). This exemplifies a synthesis reaction where two simple molecular substances combine to form a more complex compound, representing one of the most fundamental chemical reactions in nature.']

['Iron metal reacts with elemental sulfur (S₈) to form iron(II) sulfide in a synthesis reaction. The balanced chemical equation is 8Fe + S₈ → 8FeS, where eight atoms of iron combine with one molecule of cyclooctasulfur to produce eight formula units of iron(II) sulfide. This represents a classic synthesis reaction where two simple substances combine to form a more complex compound.', 'Hydrogen gas reacts with oxygen gas to form water in a synthesis reaction. The reaction follows the general pattern A + B → AB, where dihydrogen (H₂) and dioxygen (O₂) combine to produce water (H₂O), demonstrating how simple molecules can combine to form more complex compounds in synthesis reactions.']
['Formation of iron(II) sulfide from iron and sulfur: 8 Fe + S_8 → 8 FeS', 'Reaction of hydrogen and oxygen gases to produce water: 2 H_2 + O_2 → 2 H_2O']

['Formation of iron(II) sulfide: eight iron atoms (Fe) combine with one cyclooctasulfur molecule (S8) to give eight units of iron(II) sulfide (FeS). The overall stoichiometry is 8 Fe + S8 → 8 FeS.', 'Synthesis of water: two molecules of hydrogen gas (H2) react with one molecule of oxygen gas (O2) to produce two molecules of water (H2O). The overall stoichiometry is 2 H2 + O2 → 2 H2O.']

['The classic synthesis reaction described combines elemental iron (Fe) with elemental sulfur (S) to form iron(II) sulfide (FeS). In its stoichiometric form the reaction is written as 8\u202fFe + S₈ → 8\u202fFeS, but the underlying transformation can be represented by the simple combination of one iron atom with one sulfur atom to give one FeS unit.', 'Another typical synthesis reaction, though not detailed with SMILES here, would be the combination of hydrogen (H₂) and oxygen (O₂) to form water (H₂O). The focus of this extraction is on the iron‑sulfur example.']

['The synthesis of iron(II) sulfide from elemental iron and cyclooctasulfur: eight iron atoms react with one S8 molecule to produce eight FeS units (simplified as Fe + S8 -> FeS).', 'The synthesis of water from hydrogen and oxygen gases: two hydrogen molecules react with one oxygen molecule to produce two water molecules (simplified as H2 + O2 -> H2O).']
